                CAN A HIF SUPPORT A CU WHICH HAS 255 DEVICES
                --------------------------------------------
                --------------------------------------------


Written by : Dianna Tai, HQ Network Staff Consultant
      Date : January 9, 1986




      In an IBM protocol, one CU can assign a unique address, up to 32 
   devices as shown below:

              CU or Device #        EBCDIC HEX
              --------------        ----------
                 0                       40
                 1                       C1
                 .                       .
                 .                       .
                31                       5F                            

      For a configuration having more than 32 devices, more CU(s) are 
   required.  To support  255 devices, you have to have at least 8 CUs, each 
   with a maximum of 32 devices defined in the DEFDEV macro.

      When the host accesses a device, it uses the CU address and the DEVICE
   address, defined in the tymfile, to uniquely select this device.  So even
   if we can define all these 255 devices in the tymfile by defining 8 CUs,
   all with the same CU addresses, as each device will have the same CU-DEVICE 
   address combination with 7 other devices, the HOST will have a problem in
   accessing the devices correctly.



                                     06
                                  --------


             THE USE OF NMPORT, NSCNBF AND NBBFLT IN HIF TYMFILE
             ---------------------------------------------------
             ---------------------------------------------------     


Written by : Dianna Tai, HQ Network Staff Consultant
      Date : January 13, 1986




      The NMPORT and NSCNBF are only used for the Virtual Host Mode. If you 
   have CMT mode, defining them does not help the performance but does take up 
   memory space while genning the HIF. 
     
      If you let NBBFLT be defaulted and get a warning message during slot 
   gen, that is normal, simply just ignore it. However, if slot gen cannot be
   completed due to lack of memory space, then you need to modify the 
   configuration.

      The default for NBBFLT (# of big bufferlet) is based on the number of 
   lines and ports assigned to the interface. Each bufferlet has a fixed size 
   # of bytes (BBFLSZ=60 HEX). The formula to calculate the default in high 
   level language is:

      if NPORT > NDEVM then
         NBBFLT = (NDEVM + NBILIN*2) * MINBUF + BUFLO
      else
         NBBFLT = (NPORT + NBILIN*2) * MINBUF + BUFLO
      endif
      NBBFLT = NBBFLT + 80 (to insure got enough)


      (NBBFLT EQ -1 is a way of setting the bufferlets to maximum possible)
      Note:

      NFMPORT, NSCNBF, NBBFLT-- refer to I32RDH.DOC page 31 and 48.
      NPORT: # of ports
      NDEVM: # of devices
      NBILIN: # of bisync lines
      MINBUF: approx min # of buffers required per EDF MSG, set to HEX 10
      BUFLO: danger level for buffer free list, set to decimal 15. 


                                     07
                                  --------


                          CIRCUMVENT NSR LIMITATION
                          -------------------------
                          -------------------------


Written by : Mike Lucido, Mgr. Interface Support, HQ
      Date : April 25, 1985




      We all welcomed the NSR Database System, when it was introduced last
   March.  However, we soon realized there were some limitations which we
   could not live with.  One of these limitations was that only one user could
   make inquiries at a time.  That limitation is now history.  I have put
   together a program to circumvent this downfall.  All you need is access to
   the CCTS system via a logon ID and a password.  An initial procedure needs
   to be followed, but after that, a simple command will invoke the NSR system.
   The instructions follow:

   1)  Log on to the CTTS system:
          Please log in:  CTTSnnn^R^D;pw
          (nnn = your assigned id number; pw = the assigned password)

   2)  Copy the executive program (EXEC) to your system by doing the following
          LINK NSRRPT 191 199 RR NSRRPT
          ACC 199 G
          COPY NSRLINK EXEC G = = A
          REL G(DET
       (you only need to do this once.  Access to the NSR system will be
       limited to the following command:)

   3)  Invoke the NSR system:
          NSRLINK

      From this point on, you are in the NSR system.  Please contact me if you
   have any questions.  Happy NSRing!

                              **************

   A sample console listing follows:          

   C>link nsrrpt 91 199 rr nsrrpt
  
   R; T=0.01/0.01 13:35:27


   C>acc 199 g

   G (199) R/O

   R; T=0.01/0.02 13:35:54


   C>rel g(det

   G (199) DETACHED

   R; T=0.01/0.03 13:36:02


   C>nsrlink

   A (199) R/O


   ENTER REPORT OPTION ( STATUS or PENDING or COMPLETE or PRODUCT or CUSTOM or
   ALL or DOC or HELP or QUIT )




                                     09
                                  --------


                         CONCORD 224 AUTODIAL MODEMS
                         ---------------------------
                         ---------------------------


Written by : Bryan Wing, HQ Network Staff Consultant
      Date : January, 1986




      A word of caution. . .There are some limitations involved with using the
Concord 224 Autodial modems in conjunction with the current async outdial 
service.  Since the Concord 224 does not "wake up" until it receives dtr along
with a carriage return, the Tymcom will have to be set for psig(ifup).  This 
configuration ignores modem signals for all purposes for connection and 
disconnection.  It is preferrable to use the pcan(sig) option, but since the 
modem needs signals from the Tymcom first, this is impossible.  What will 
inevitably occur is a user landing on a port that has either no modem attached
or a defective modem or a loose cable and the call will stay connected.  
The user will have a hung session.

      Dave Peters, in Tymnet Marketing, is currently working with Concord to
reslove this issue.



