                                  --------


      TEST RESULTS TAKEN FROM THROUGHPUT TESTER READINGS OF TYMCOM 2.03
      -----------------------------------------------------------------
      -----------------------------------------------------------------


Written by : Bryan Wing
      Date : Jan 27, 1986




   The following tables reflect results from many tests taken from throughput
   tester readings of Tymcom performance.  These results represent the best
   cases of closed environment tests.  Output totals declined rapidly once
   these values were attained.  No buffer zap messages were elicitted although
   I suspect data was lost.

   The intent of the tests was to find the peak output.  To do this, it was
   necessary to start at a low output and gradually increase the output level.
   Starting the throughput tester output at a high level, such as 240 cps,
   always produced horrible results.  Other readings showed identical results
   for a certain range of ports.  This leads me to distrust the throughput
   tester's readings to a degree.


   High speed interrupts were enabled and only slots (1) and (2) were 
   utilized.  Tymcom code ran in slot (1) and throughput tester code ran in 
   slot (2).  No synchronous input or output was involved except for channel
   (0) network communication.




   This first table represents the best, and I must repeat best, readings for
   (4) ports with throughput tester output set at 480 cps.


   CPS RATES:       INPUT       OUTPUT       COMBINED
       TOTAL:        1598         1416           3014
     AVERAGE:         399          354            753


   This second table represents the best results for (8) ports with throughput
   tester output set at 240 cps.


   CPS RATES:       INPUT       OUTPUT       COMBINED
       TOTAL:        2168         1928           4096
     AVERAGE:         271          241            512


   This third table represents the best results for (16) ports with throughput
   tester output set at 120 cps.

   CPS RATES:       INPUT       OUTPUT       COMBINED
    TOTAL:        2048         1617           3665
  AVERAGE:         128          101            229


   I must emphasize that these figures are very optomistic.  I have seen
   instances where throughput has been degraded with fewer async ports active
   and high speed interrupts are enabled.  Buffer zaps will occur especially
   with high input levels.  In extreme cases, I would not count out a crash
   of the slot.  This is as definitive an answer that is available at this 
   time.  This is for Tymcom code only.  Consat code performs much worse.
   No degradation readings are available for compilation.


  

   I have attached, below, the throughput statistics (by Dave Smith) for
   version 2.00 & 2.01:


               ASYNC TYMCOM VERSION 2.00 THROUGHPUT STATISTICS
               -----------------------------------------------
               -----------------------------------------------


   Many of you have asked for publishable throughput statistics for the 
   Version 2.00 Async Tymcom slot.  The following statistics have been 
   released by NTD, and can be found in the document (BASELINE:39,25,70)
   ACOM02.Y01.  

   The tests were done first for Version 2.00 in foreground, then for Version
   2.01 in background.  The data flow originated at a throughput host slot,
   residing in te same node as the Async Tymcom slot, acting as 15 user
   terminals.  The conclusion is that data in this direction can be compared
   to data originating at the host.  Because the throughput host resided in 
   the same node, bandwidth considerations were not necessary.  The CPU
   utilized by the throughput host could be compared to the node code CPU use,
   if necessary.

   The data was specified as burst size 10, cps 120.  This meant the data was
   received at the Tymcom slot in 10 character messages at an approximate rate
   equal to a 1200 baud terminal.

   Note:  the ideal, non-degraded throughput would be 1800 CPS for one 
   direction, 3600 bi-directional.  The formula:  
              
                       15 ports X 120 CPS =  1800 CPS


   Interrupt Type                        Total Slot CPS
   --------------                        --------------
   Foreground - output only
   1200 async                            1700
   4800 async                            1500
   SIO                                   1800
   Foreground - loopback, both directions measured
   1200 async                            2000
   4800 async                            1600
   SIO                                   3000
   Background - loopback, both directions measured
   1200 async                            2500
   4800 async                            2000
   SIO                                   3200



