                                  --------


               TIPS ON NETVAL VERSION III AND NVDM VERSION II
            PREPARED FOR PRIVATE NETWORK PROJECT MANAGER TRAINING
            -----------------------------------------------------
            -----------------------------------------------------


Written by : Jeff Liu, HQ Technical Svc, Application's Support Dept.
      Date : January, 6, 1986





                              Table of Contents
                              -----------------
  
                   1.0 Overview.
                   2.0 Netval Concepts.
                       2.1 CUD/MUD Contents.
                   3.0 Supervisor updating.
                       3.1 MUD updating.
                   3.2 Class/group table updating.
                   4.0 Operator log.
                   5.0 Logical volume.
                       5.1 Logical volume commands.
                   6.0 NETVAL & NVDM Memory Configuration.
                   7.0 NETVAL Disk Maintenance Program (NVDM).








  SECTION 1.0 Overview
  --------------------
  The NETVAL program is used to validate TYMNET network users  and  to
  determine  how much access a user has within a network.  NETVAL runs
  in a slot in the Internally Switched Interface System  (ISIS)  on  a
  TYMNET node.

  SECTION 2.0 Concept
  -------------------
  The CUD, or Controlling User Directory, is a file which contains  an
  entry for each valid user in the network.  When changes are made via
  NETVAL, they are made directly to CUD file a record of  each  change
  also appended to the MUDUPDATE file.

  The MUD, or Master User Directory.  Each supervisor in  the  network
  has its own copy of the CUD on its own disk, reffered to as the MUD.

  In order for the supervisors to be accessing up-to-date data, NETVAL
  uses the information in the MUDUPDATE file to notify each Supervisor
  of all the CUD changes.  There is  an  automatic  process  for  each
  supervisor of the change.

  SECTION 2.1 CUD MUD Contents
  ----------------------------
  USERNAME : Up to 20 characters.  The acceptable  characters  consist
             of:
      1.  all alph-numeric characters.
      2.  the characters: <space>   $  *  , .  - /
  ENTRY CHANGE DATE PASSWORD CIPHER : Up to 30 characters any character
      other than a semicolon, null, rub-out, escape, or carriage return
      may be useed.  
  PASSWORD  CHANGEDATE 
  UNIVERSAL  USER  NAME (UUN) : 0 - 37777777777 (octal).  
  GLOBAL ACCOUNT NUMBER (GAN) - optional : Group user together under a
      single account.   range  0  - 37777777777.  
  CONTROL OPTIONS :
      AUDITOR OPERATOR 
      ACCOUNT SUPERVISOR
      NETWORK SUPERVISOR
      IGNORE HOST 
      NO PASSWORD
      SHUT OVERRIDE
      TRANSPARENT LOGIN
      DISTRICT  - optional 
  HOME : A default termination point for a  circuit  if no termination
         host is included in the login string or if the user  has  the
         ignore host option. 
  HOST : A host number is an address antity in  the network from which
         a  circuit  can  be  built.
  ACCESS PROFILE
      ORIGIN : Class.
      DESTINATION : Group.




  SECTION 3.0 Supervisor updating
  -------------------------------
  Netval is a Network Validation program  that  allows  validators  to
  make  changes  to  network validation data on the Netval system, and
  automatically transmits these changes to network Supervisors.  These
  data that is handled by Netval includes:

  1. CUD/MUD Information:
     When a user attempts to login through the network, the Supervisor
     uses the  information  in  its  MUD to determine the user's legal
     access.
     * Is the user name in MUD?
     * Is the passwords correct?
     * Can  user  originate  from the node or host that he is entering
       the network from?
     * Can user access the host specified as a destination?
     * Which  host  should  the user  be  routed  to  if there is none
       specified in the login string? etc.

  2. Class/group information
  Part of the user's CUD/MUD entry contains access information,  i.e.,
  legal network origins and destination for users.

  CLASS : is a  globally  defined  set  of  originating  hosts  and/or
  originating nodes, which are used to define the locations from which
  a user may access the network (ORIGINS).   GROUP  :  is  a  globally
  defined  set  of host numbers.  Groups are used to define the set of
  host to which a user may build a circuit.  (DESTINATION).

  Netval maintains information about Classes and groups, and generates
  a  copy  of  supervisor  Class/group Table; each supervisor uses its
  Class/ Group Table when a user is logging  in,  and  the  users  MUD
  entry refers to a CLASS an origin or a GROUP as a destination.

  In both above cases, validators login to Netval and make changes  to
  Netval  information.   Netval  then  transmits  the  changes  to the
  supervisors.

  When transmitting CUD data, Netval communicates with the  UN2  slave
  part  of  the supervisor; When transmitting Class/Group data, Netval
  communicates with the SYSMSG1 Slave part of the Supervisor.

  It is important that the validation information gets updated on  the
  Supervisors  in  a timely manner.  Out-of-date information may cause
  users to lose access through the network, or may grant access  to  a
  user that should no longer have it.  

  Netval maintains a list of "legal" supervisors, the supervisors that
  have  been  turned  "on"  in Netval with the SET SUPERVISOR Command.
  There are the supervisors that Netval will  update  when  there  are
  changes made to CUD or Class/Group Table.
    



  READ TABLE  comman  allows  the  validator  to display a Class/Group
  table.
  If the  optional  argument <sup> is included, the supervisor's table
  will  be read  and  displayed.  if the argument is omitted, NETVAL's 
  table will be displayed.

  *REAd Table <sup> 
  Origins available : 520
  Destinations available : 1760
  Class 1:
    nodes: 1121, 1437, 2249
  Class 2:
    hosts: 47, 22, 34
    nodes: 1017, 1018, 1019, 2001, 2002, 2003
  Class 3: 
    nodes except: 1317, 2124, 2248
         .
         .
         .
  Class 22 - 25: Undefined
  Group 1:
    hosts except: 123, 350, 149, 78, 134, 54, 67, 76
  Group 2:
    hosts: 2, 3, 6, 7, 8, 9
         .
         .
         .
  Group 9 - 10: undefined
  

  SECTION 3.1 MUD Updating
  ------------------------
  When a modification is made to the Netval CUD, a description of  the
  change  is appended to the MUDUPDATE file.  An automatic process for
  each supervisor is notified that there is a change  to  be  sent,  a
  circuit  is  built  to  Supervisor,  and  the  change is transmitted
  through the network.  Only the changed information is sent.
  Network keeps track of how much data is in the file (the  file  EOF)
  and  the  point to which each Supervisor has been updated.  When the
  data has been sent to all legal supervisors, the EOF is set to 0.
  If a supervisor is "Down" (inaccessible to Netval) for a  period  of
  times  the  data  in the MUDUPDATE file may come close to filling up
  the file.  If the MUDUPDATE file ever becomes full, VALIDATORS  WILL
  NO  LONGER  BE ABLE TO MAKE CHANGES TO THE CUD.  A supervisor may be
  turned "off" with the SET SUPERVISOR s OFF command.

  CONSISTENCY :
     * SET SCHEDULE  Command, once a day a consistency process is run.
     * RUN_AUTO_CONSISTENCY_ON_SUP_INIT  parameter  set to true in the
       config  file, a consistency  will  start  up  immediately  when
       the SET SUPERVISOR  command is executed. 
     * Manual  consistency  is  run  whenever  there  is a doubt as to
       whether the MUD contains up-to-date information.

       It compares  checksums  between  CUD and MUD blocks, and if the
       MUD checksum does  not  match  the  CUD checksum, the CUD block 
       data is to be stored in the MUD.



  SECTION 3.2 Class/group Table Updating
  --------------------------------------
  The  Class/Group  Table  information  is   maintained   by   Network
  Administrator validators.  When the class/group Table is ready to be
  transmitted to the supervisors the SEND command is executed.
  This causes a date (class/group table last created) to be set to the
  current  time.   An automatic process continually compares this time
  against the time that the table was last sent  to  each  Supervisor,
  and  if  necessary, transmits a copy of the Table to any out-of-date
  Supervisors.

  *display updates
  Current time is 12/07/84 02:20:39 GMT
  Blocks in CUD: 2039  MUD update EOF: 294  (0% full)
  Class and Group table last created: 12/06/83 08:42:02
  Scheduled consistency period: 01:00 to 04:00
  Sup                      MUD        Class and Group
             ptr         updated          Updated
  121             4     12/05 11:02      12/05 13:42
  122           294     12/07 01:42      12/06 12:40
  124             4     12/06 12:03      12/06 08:43
  125           294     12/07 02:12      12/06 08:44
  127            56     12/07 02:45      12/07 01:20
                           CONSISTENCY
       Last Start     Last Stop   End Block    Current Start  Block
  121  12/05 01:01    12/05 02:00  complete
  122  12/06 01:01    12/06 01:15    102     S
  124  12/06 01:03    12/06 02:26   1205        12/07 01:15      45
  125  12/06 01:02    12/06 02:25  complete     12/07 01:03    2030 M
  127  12/07 00:05    12/07 01:15  complete  M


  SECTION 4.0 Operator Log
  ------------------------
  Netval maintains a log of information about critical events  in  the
  Netval system, This includes validator logins, logouts, disk errors,
  and  the  execution   of   critical   operational   commands(Setting
  Supervisors,    consistency,   schedule,   etc.).    If   the   flag
  CHANGE_TO_OPERLOG is enabled in the Netval configuration  file.  The
  MESSAGE command is used to display information from the operator log
  file.


  SECTION 5.0 Logical Volumes
  ---------------------------
  In NETVAL version 3, if the configuration  parameter LOGICAL_VOLUMES
  is  Enabled in the Netval configuration file, the engine must have 2
  physical disk drives.  An ISIS  logical  unit  is  defined  on  each
  physical disk drives for the CUD and file system.  The "CUD" logical
  units include the CUD and the CUD parameter file; the "file  system"
  logical units include all other Netval files.





       Physical Drive 0                Physical Drive 1
    _______________________         _______________________
   /  UNIT 0     UNIT 1    \       /  UNIT 0     UNIT 1    \
  |           |             |     |           |             |
  |   CUD     | Config,time |     |   CUD     | Config,time |
  |           | stamp.      |     |           | stamp.      |
  | CUD param | Node/host,  |     | CUD param | Node/host,  |
  |           | Class/Group,|     |           | Class/Group,|
  |           | Mud change, |     |           | Mud change, |
  |           | Operator log|     |           | Operator log|
  \___________|_____________/     \___________|_____________/
       |             |                  |            |
       |             |                  |            |
       |             \_________________ | ___________/
       \________________________________/
  

  SECTION 5.1 Logical Volume Commands
  -----------------------------------
  COPY : The COPY commands causes data to be read  from  one  physical
  disk  (in  read/write  state)  and copies to the same sectors on the
  other physical disk (in the down or offline state).  Once  the  copy
  operation  starts,  the state of the disk being copied TO is changed
  to write only.  At the end of COPY command, the state  of  the  disk
  being copied TO is changed to read/write state.

  If  neither  disk  is  down  or offline, the user receives the error
  message:
       one disk must be down or offline
  IF a copy is already being performed  on  the  system, user receives
  message:
       A copy is already in progress

  If the above  criteria  are  satisfied,  the  COPY  Command  display
  Logical  volume  information,  and  prompts  for confirmation of the
  direction of the copy.

  DISPLAY LVOL: It will display current  logical  volume  information.
  It can be used to monitor the current drive states.

  SET Drive d OFFLine : It will set the specified drive,  "d"  to  the
  offline  state;  it  should  be  used by an operator when a drive is
  known to be faulty, the data on a disk is suspect, or when preparing
  to remove a pack from the system.
















  SECTION 6.0 NETVAL & NVDM Memory Config
  ---------------------------------------


   ------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                                Additional
                     Operating Version   Base    Memory    Disk     Tape
   Product Processor  System   of code   code    Needed    Drives   Drives
   ------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Netval  Engine    ISIS        1       187 KB     0      1-2      1-4

   Netval  Engine    ISIS        2       302 KB     *      1-2      1-4
   NVDM    Engine    ISIS        1       302 KB     0      1-2      1-4

   Netval  Engine    ISIS        3       290 KB     **     1-2      1-4
   NVDM    Engine    ISIS        2       290 KB     0      1-2      1-4
   ------------------------------------------------------------------------

   * 4 KB/additional Supervisor node
     5 KB/additional password-only user
    12 KB/additional authorized NETVAL user

  ** ( CB = sectors in CUD block; TB = sectors in Class/group Table )
     each licenced user,          add:  (2k * CB) + (0.25k * TB)
     each password only user,     add:  3k + (0.5k * CB)
     each Supervisor,             add:  2k + (0.5k * CB)
     LOGICAL_VOLUMES enabled,     add: 64k
     REUSE_UUNS enabled,          add: 13k
     OVERFLOW_CUD_ENTRIES enabled add:  3k
     VALIDATE_x25_NAMES enabled,  add:  2k
     NETVAL_IS_A_SLAVE enabled,   add: 16k
     each master user,            add:  4k + (1k * CB)
     Tymnet,                      add: 10k


  





















  SECTION 7.0 NETVAL Disk Maintenance Program (NVDM)
  --------------------------------------------------
  NETVAL Disk Maintenance Program (NVDM) is used  to  perform  certain
  NETVAL  disk and tape operations.  The NVDM program runs in the same
  ISIS slot as NETVAL, but not at the same time.

  NVDM is used to initialize  or  reformat  the  NETVAL  disk  and  to
  reconfigure  files.   NVDM  is also used to display information from
  the NETVAL disk.

  NVDM has its own archive subsystem, which is used  to  perform  tape
  operations.   The  NVDM  user  can use the NVDM archive subsystem to
  restore files from tape to disk.  All tape files can be restored  in
  one  operation.   Some specific files such as the CUD file, can also
  be restored.

  Only the NETVAL user at highest authorization level and a  specially
  designed NVDM operator validator are authorized to use NVDM.





                                     46
                                  --------


                          RAM OPERATIONAL PROBLEMS
                          ------------------------
                          ------------------------


Written by : Jan Smith, HQ Technical Svc, Application's Support Dept.
      Date : Jan 13, 1986

             


       Current fully relesed versions of RAM are RAM  version  10.05  and
       RAM  version  10.07.   Current  Betatest  versions  of RAM are RAM
       version 11.04 and RAM version 11.05.  

       Problems that  may  be  encountered  in  the  operation  of  these
       versions are:

         o  For Versions other than 11.05, RAM goes haywire if all slaves
            are declared down and RAM is allowed to RUN.

         o  RAM may at times have a communication problem with the slaves
            which  is  often  corrected by issuing a SLAVE/UP command for
            the slave in question.

         o  RAM may need to be  restarted  due  to  a  crash,  change  of
            version,  or  necessity  for disk or tape maintenance.  It is
            best to  restaret  RAM  with  a  WARMSTART  command  whenever
            possible.  If a new version of RAM is loaded or the data from
            the last RAM backup no longer resides on  the  RAM  disk,  it
            will  be  necessary  to  follow  the  COLDSTART  procedure as
            outlined in the RAM Operator Guide.  If  the  crash  occurred
            while  RAM  was in the RUN state, it is likely that RAM would
            have stopped in the middle of a  file  and  consequently  the
            tape  would not have been ended with two tape marks.  If this
            should happen and RAM does not require  a  COLDSTART,  it  is
            best  to  use  the  ATTACH/BACK  and  WARMSTART  commands  to
            reposition the tape at the point of the last backup  and  RAM
            will  continue  processing from the point of the last backup.
            The ATTACH/BACK command has a bug in version 10.05.

         o  Use of the SETBLOCK command without issueing a  COLDSTART  in
            conjunction  with  the  SETBLOCK command can cause incomplete
            sessions to be written to tape.  This  could  happen  if  RAM
            were  instructed  to recollect previously collected SUP data.
            The COLDSTART command clears the  table  RAM  uses  to  track
            session records.

         o  If RAM generates a tape that is unreadable, there could be  a
            problem  in  recreating  the  tape.   Version  11.05 has tape
            duplication capabilities as long as the tape has been  backed
            up  to  disk.   An option exists in version 11.05 to backup a
            specified number of tape images to  disk.   It  is  virtually
            impossible  to  recollect  RAM  data and expect to produce an
            exact image of a previous tape.  A set of tapes collected  on
            one  drive  and  a  second  set of tapes collected on another
            drive can produce two  sets  containing  complete  accounting
            data  if  the  procedure  is  followed as outlined in the RAM
            Operators Guide.  The procedure requires that the  collection
            process  for  each tape begin with a COLDSTART and end with a
            DRAIN.  The  DRAIN  writes  out  incomplete  session  records
            remaining in memory.

         o  If a second tape unit is attached and on-line when the  first
            unit  fails,  RAM  will write to the tape on the second unit.
            However the labeling information for the second tape will  be
            the same as that for the first tape.

         o  RAM's normal collection process may be interrupted  following
            a  DUMP  command  if  the  RAM pointer is not reset.  (May be
            reset by the SETBLOCK command)

         o  The RAM session pool will fill up frequently  if  not  enough
            memory  is  allocated  for  the  expected load of the Network
            involved.

         o  Testing RAM with continual logons will  produce  an  abnormal
            number of sessions and cause the session pool to fill.

         o  RAM may report that the disk is down if  the  wrong  type  of
            disk  controller  is  specified  in  the  slot tymfile or not
            enough space was allocated for a disk backup in the DSC file.

         o  If only one supervisor is reported on the status report  with
            possibly  the  wrong  number, it could be that a count of the
            number of  supervisors  was  given  in  the  SUPERS  paramter
            instead of each supervisors number.

         o  Garbage such as host numbers and passwords  may  show  up  in
            RAM's  project code field depending on how interfaces such as
            the TYMCOM are set up to report this  data.   This  might  be
            avoided  by  regenning  the interface not to report a project
            code or have the interface specify  to  the  ISIS  delimiters
            such  as  a  carriage  return or ";" in receiving the project
            code.

         o  The report generated by the STATUS command will  not  reflect
            the  results  of  the  SETBLOCK  command  until after the RUN
            command is executed.



                                     48
                                  --------


                            X.25 and the "BIGIO"
                            --------------------
                            --------------------


Written by : Mary Lou Harline, HQ Network Staff Consultant
      Date : Jan 28, 1986


     Version 3.01 of the XCOM code allows for much larger systems
     than previous versions.  BIGIO is intended to help with BIG
     systems, but it isn't needed until you get REALLY BIG systems.
     
     Baseline Document XCOM03.Z01 states (Section B.3, page 2):
        "Switch BIGIO will effect the memory requirements of
        the interface.  When ON more memory will be required.
        An assembly time warning message will indicate when it
        must be turned ON."

     What happens if your system is TOO BIG?
     At the start of assembly of XCOM03.R01, a WARNING message will
     appear:

        "Configuration too large -- reduce either number of links, 
        MAXPSIZE, or MAXK, or use 2[BIGIO in CMD file."

     What is TOO BIG?
     It is not possible to make a general statement because of the
     variety of parameters, but the following configuration was genned
     without assembly errors, and WITHOUT 2[BIGIO:.
          512 DPORTS
          4 HOSTS
          10 LINKS (10 had packet size 512, packet window size 127,
                    2 had large frame size - MAXK(127)).

     Because of the large number of DPORTS, P0SIZE had to be increased
     to 1000 (this was also true with 255 DPORTS).  
     The final size was 664d K-bytes of core.

     You will probably not need to worry about getting a 2[BIGIO 
     message for your usual systems, but watch for PATCH0 area 
     overflow with lots of DPORTS.

     DO NOT use 2[BIGIO unless you are told to--and even then consider
     reducing one of the three sensitive parameters:  number of links,
     MAXPSIZE, or MAXK.

                   DOCUMENTS TO BE MADE AVAILABLE

     COMMENT ON THE HELPFUL DOCUMENTS ON THE BASELINE DIRECTORY:
     Baseline Software Release Form XCOM03.X01, Software Release
     Description XCOM03.Y01, and Document Change Description 
     XCOM03.Z01, all mention supporting documentation on System 39.

     These will soon be available on another system.  Don't
     give up if you don't have access to System 39.



