                   IBM ABNORMAL DISCONNECT/SECURITY ISSUE
                   --------------------------------------
                   --------------------------------------
                   

Written by : Mary Chalmers, IBM Product Mgr.
      Date : January 28, 1986




   IBM ABNORNAL DISCONNECT/SECURITY ISSUE
 
   IBM host application programs have no standardized  method of
   accepting an "abnormal disconnect" sequence and closing end users
   sessions. The open session issue exists any time you introduce
   "switching" into an IBM data communications environment.  This
   includes not only Tymnet and other VAN's but also IBM's own SNA
   Network Interconnect products. Tymnet's IBM Host Interfaces have
   the capability to notify the IBM host to close its session.
   Tymnet has been working with our customers and outside software
   vendors to find workable solutions to close host sessions and
   "clean up" data queues.

   THE ISSUE

   The possibility of one end user getting into another end users
   open IBM host session and/or one end user getting data that was
   meant for another end user.     
 
   Example 1 : User 1 does not log out of their CICS session but
   unplugs the modem instead.  Tymnet will cancel the circuit and
   may send a "notification" to the IBM host.  It is the CICS on the
   IBM host that is responsible for understanding the "notification"
   and closing the end users session.

   Example 2: User 1 does not log out of their IMS session but
   unplugs the modem instead.  Tymnet will cancel the circuit and
   may send a "notification" to the IBM host.  It would then be up
   to IMS application program to cleanup user 1's data que's.
   Instead IMS is designed to hold that data until that LU logs on
   again.  Since Tymnet "shares" LU's among multiple end users user
   1's data will end up in someone else hands.  This is considered
   an unacceptable security violation by many customers.
 
   Example 3 :  User 1 disconnects abnormally.  Tymnet sends nothing
   or something that the IBM host can not interpret as "close the LU
   session".  The next end user will get into the open host session
   and will have bypassed any host security logons and/or passwords.

   CONCLUSION

   Tymnet has worked closing with our customers to find solutions
   for these issues.  The following are technical discussions that
   describe how various Tymnet customer have implemented successful
   systems with various IBM host applications.

   The setting of the disconnect sequence must be done VERY
   CAREFULLY by someone who is intimately familiar with IBM link
   level protocols.  The improper setting of a disconnect could
   cause undesirable reactions from a host system.
 



   CICS--Abnormal Disconnect
 
   Bisync systems running CICS version 1.6 and lower.
 
   Most CICS systems will close a session upon an abnormal
   disconnect if they are sent a Sense and Status message.
   Tymnet's Bisync Host Interface version 7.05 has a patch avialable
   from HQTech that will send any Sense/Status code that the
   customer needs. The customers CICS systems programmer should
   check the CICS Terminal error program, Terminal control program
   and/or Node abnormal condition program to determine what
   Sense/Status code should be used at their installation.
 
   NOTE:  DETERMINING THE CORRECT SENSE/STATUS IS THE CUSOMTERS
   REPONSIBILITY.  TRYING TO GUESS CAN BE VERY DANGEROUS IN BISYNC
   SYSTEMS. WHILE THE MOST COMMONLY FOUND SENSE/STATUS IS `C240'
   OR`D240', CICS SYSTEM TABLES MUST BE CHECKED BY THE CUSTOMERS
   SYSTEMS PROGRAMER TO DETERMINE THE EFFECT OF THE SENSE/STATUS
   SELECTED.  THE SENSE/STATUS SHOULD ONLY CLOSE A SINGLE SESSION
   AND NOT BE SET TO DISCONNECT OTHER USERS OR BRING DOWN THE ENTIRE
   CICS APPLICATION.

   Other technical concerns:

       1. CICS Terminal Control Table--if users can not log on after
       an abnormal disconnect the customers CICS programmer needs to
       check the RELREQ parameter.  If it is not there or is 
       RELREQ=(no,no), which is the IBM default, you have found a
       problem.  The table must be regened with the second
       parameter set to yes.
 
       RELREQ=(no,yes) or RELREQ=(yes,yes) or RELREQ=(,yes)
    
       2.  The VTAM exit LOSTERM may also effect the
       processing of the disconnect sequence. LOSTERM is the VTAM
       exit responsible for interpret and processing the
       sense/status to the host application.

   Reference: Customer Information Control System/Virtual Storage
   (CICS/VS) Version 1 Release 5--System Progrmmer's Reference
   Manual--SC33-0069-4, July 1981
 
   If problems still exist RFI *** BSC

   SNA/SDLC CICS Systems
 
   When the host interface get the Zapper it will send a SNA/SDLC
   Terminate-Self command to the IBM host.  Although the TERM-SELF
   is not documented as a valid 3270 command it does work.  If a
   customer is still having problems have the customers systems
   programmer check:
 
 
       1. If users can not log on after an abnormal disconnect the
       customers CICS programmer needs to check the RELREQ parameter
       of the CICS TCT table.  If it is not there or is
       RELREQ=(no,no), which is the IBM default, you have found a
       problem.  The table must be regened with the second parameter
       set to yes.
 
       RELREQ=(no,yes) or RELREQ=(yes,yes)  or RELREQ=(,yes)  are
       the recommended parameters.
 
 
       Reference: Customer Information Control System/Virtual
       Storage (CICS/VS) Version 1 Release 5--System Progrmmer's
       Reference Manual--SC33-0069-4, July 1981

       2.  VTAM Logmode table--most systems use an "orderly
       termination" ;however, some may need "forced termination".
       In this case, byte 3 bit 2 of the TERM-SELF will need to be
       adjusted.
 
                 0 forced termination--session is deactivated 
                        immediately and unconditionaly
                 1 orderly termination--permitting an end-of-session
                        procedure to be executed at the PLU before
                        the session is deavtivated (this is the
                        default)

       3.  If the problem still exists RFI *** SNA for further
       assistance.
 
 
 
 
   TSO--Abnormal Disconnect
 
   Bisync systems running TSO 
 
   Most TSO systems will close a session upon an abnormal disconnect
   if they are sent a Sense/Status message. Tymnet's Bisync Host
   Interface version 7.05 has a patch avialable from HQTech that
   will send any Sense/Status code that the customer needs. The
   customers TSO systems programmer should check the TSO system
   tables to determine the proper code.

 
   Note:  The most commonly found default is `C240' but have
   customer check to be sure.

   Other technical concerns:

       1.  The VTAM paramenter LOSTERM may also effect the
       processing of the disconnect sequence.

 
       2.  If problems still exist RFI *** BSC

   SNA/SDLC TSO Systems
 
   When the host interface get the Zapper it will send a SNA/SDLC
   Terminate-Self command to the IBM host.  Although the TERM-SELF
   is not documented as a valid 3270 command it does work.  If a
   customer is still having problems have the customers systems
   programmer check:
 
       1.  VTAM Logmode table--most systems use an "orderly
       termination" ; however, some may need "forced termination".
       In this case, byte 3 bit 2 of the TERM-SELF will need to be
       adjusted.
 
                 0 forced termination--session is deactivated 
                        immediately and unconditionaly
                 1 orderly termination--permitting an end-of-session
                         procedure to be executed at the PLU before
                         the session is deavtivated

       2.  If the problem still exists RFI *** SNA for further
       assistance.
 
 
 
 
   VM--Abnormal disconnect
 
   Bisync systems running VM 
 
   Most VM systems will close a session upon an abnormal
   disconnect if they are sent a Sense and Status message.
   if they are sent a Sense/Status message. Tymnet's Bisync Host
   Interface version 7.05 has a patch avialable from HQTech that
   will send any Sense/Status code that the customer needs. The
   customers VM systems programmer should check the VM system tables
   to determine the proper code.
 
   Note:  The most commonly found default is `C240' but have
   customer check to be sure.

   Other technical concerns:

       1.  The VTAM paramenter LOSTERM may also effect the
       processing of the disconnect sequence.

 
       2.  If problems still exist RFI *** BSC

   SNA/SDLC VM Systems
 
   When the host interface get the Zapper it will send a SNA/SDLC
   Terminate-Self command to the IBM host.  Although the TERM-SELF
   is not documented as a valid 3270 command it does work.  If a
   customer is still having problems have the customers systems
   programmer check:
 
       1.  VTAM Logmode table--most systems use an "orderly
       termination" ; however, some may need "forced termination".
       In this case, byte 3 bit 2 of the TERM-SELF will need to be
       adjusted.
 
                 0 forced termination--session is deactivated 
                        immediately and unconditionaly
                 1 orderly termination--permitting an end-of-session
                         procedure to be executed at the PLU before
                         the session is deavtivated

       2.  If the problem still exists RFI *** SNA for further
       assistance.
 
 
 
 
   IMS--Abnormal Disconnect
 
   IMS is the most difficult of all the IBM applications to get
   cleaned up.  This is becuase IMS is designed to keep data in its
   queues even upon system failure--the least of which is a terminal
   abnormally disconnnecting from a session.   While Tymnet's IBM
   Bisync Host Interface has the flexibility to send various
   "disconnect indicators " to the IBM host it still remains the
   responsibility of the customer to have IBM host software that
   will dequeue data intended for the disconnected  session.
 
   Some Tymnet customer's have written their own VTAM
   resident "session manager" software to perform this function.
   This software recognizes a message or status or test request
   sequence from the BSC HIF which indicates a network disconnect
   has taken place.  The SNA/SDLC HIF uses the TERM-SELF as the
   network "disconnect indicator". The software then cleans up any
   data left for the disconnected session. 

   At the present time, we are working with several software
   vendors and testing several packages that  perform the "clean-up"
   function.
 
   Another option to consider is to use static network addressing
   (CRM2).
 
   If you have a client who is using IMS you should get in touch
   with Product Marketing to get the latest information on software
   packages.



